com.pb.sawdust.util.format

Enum TextFormat.DateTimeConversion

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<TextFormat.DateTimeConversion>
      • com.pb.sawdust.util.format.TextFormat.DateTimeConversion
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<TextFormat.DateTimeConversion>
    Enclosing class:
    TextFormat

    public static enum TextFormat.DateTimeConversion
extends java.lang.Enum<TextFormat.DateTimeConversion>
    The DateTimeConversion enum defines all of the date time conversions available to TextFormat instances with the conversion TextFormat.Conversion.DATE_TIME or TextFormat.Conversion.DATE_TIME_UPPER_CASE.

    • Enum Constant Summary

      Enum Constants 
      Enum Constant and Description
      AM_PM
      Locale-specific morning or afternoon marker in lower case, e.g. "am" or "pm".
      DAY
      Day of month, formatted as two digits, i.e. "1" - "31".
      DAY_366
      Day of year, formatted as three digits with leading zeros as necessary, e.g. "001" - "366" for the Gregorian calendar.
      DAY_OF_WEEK
      Locale-specific full name of the day of the week, e.g. "Sunday", "Monday".
      DAY_OF_WEEK_ABBREVIATED
      Locale-specific short name of the day of the week, e.g. "Sun", "Mon".
      DAY_TIME
      Date and time formatted as "weekday month day hour:minute:second time zone year", e.g. "Sun Jul 20 16:17:00 EDT 1969".
      DAY_ZERO_PADDED
      Day of month, formatted as two digits with leading zeros as necessary, i.e. "01" - "31".
      HOUR_12
      Hour of the day for the 12-hour clock, i.e. "0" - "12".
      HOUR_12_ZERO_PADDED
      Hour for the 12-hour clock, formatted as two digits with a leading zero as necessary, i.e. "01" - "12".
      HOUR_24
      Hour of the day for the 24-hour clock, i.e. "0" - "23".
      HOUR_24_ZERO_PADDED
      Hour of the day for the 24-hour clock, formatted as two digits with a leading zero as necessary i.e. "00" - "23".
      HOUR_MINUTE_24
      Time formatted for the 24-hour clock as "hour:minute" using HOUR_24_ZERO_PADDED for the hour and MINUTE_24_ZERO_PADDED for the minutes.
      HOUR_MINUTE_SECOND_12
      Time formatted for the 12-hour clock as "hour:minute:second marker" using HOUR_12_ZERO_PADDED for the hour, MINUTE_24_ZERO_PADDED for the minute, SECOND_24_ZERO_PADDED for the second, and AM_PM for the marker.
      HOUR_MINUTE_SECOND_24
      Time formatted for the 24-hour clock as "hour:minute:second" using HOUR_24_ZERO_PADDED for the hour, MINUTE_24_ZERO_PADDED for the minute, and SECOND_24_ZERO_PADDED for the second.
      MILLISECOND_ZERO_PADDED
      Millisecond within the second formatted as three digits with leading zeros as necessary, i.e. "000" - "999".
      MILLISECONDS_EPOCH
      Milliseconds since the beginning of the epoch starting at 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC, i.e. Long.MIN_VALUE to Long.MAX_VALUE.
      MINUTE_ZERO_PADDED
      Minute within the hour formatted as two digits with a leading zero as necessary, i.e. "00" - "59".
      MONTH
      Locale-specific full month name, e.g. "January", "February".
      MONTH_12
      Month, formatted as two digits with leading zeros as necessary, i.e. "01" - "13".
      MONTH_ABBREVIATE
      Locale-specific abbreviated month name, e.g. "Jan", "Feb".
      MONTH_DAY_YEAR
      Date formatted as "month/day/year" using MONTH_12 for the month, DAY_ZERO_PADDED for the day, and YEAR_TENS for the year.
      NANOSECOND_ZERO_PADDED
      Nanosecond within the second, formatted as nine digits with leading zeros as necessary, i.e. "000000000" - "999999999".
      SECOND_ZERO_PADDED
      Seconds within the minute, formatted as two digits with a leading zero as necessary, i.e. "00" - "60" ("60" is a special value required to support leap seconds)."
      SECONDS_EPOCH
      Seconds since the beginning of the epoch starting at 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC, i.e. Long.MIN_VALUE/1000 to Long.MAX_VALUE/1000.
      TIME_ZONE
      A string representing the abbreviation for the time zone.
      TIME_ZONE_NUMERIC
      RFC 822 style numeric time zone offset from GMT, e.g. "-0800".
      YEAR
      Year, formatted as at least four digits with leading zeros as necessary, e.g. "0092" equals 92 CE for the Gregorian calendar.
      YEAR_HUNDREDS
      Four-digit year divided by 100, formatted as two digits with leading zero as necessary, i.e. "00" - "99".
      YEAR_MONTH_DAY_ISO8601
      ISO 8601 complete date formatted as "year-month-day" using YEAR for the year, MONTH_12 for the month, and DAY_ZERO_PADDED for the day.
      YEAR_TENS
      Last two digits of the year, formatted with leading zeros as necessary, i.e. "00" - "99".
